GOOGLE PLAY STORE: ANALYSIS OF MARKET¶

Aparna, Yinghui, Kai, Jinyan, Shimiao, Sizhe

Summary:¶

We selected the following dataset about Google play store usage.Through this dataset, we hope to answer questions where we can draw inference on factors affecting the ratings and downloads of various apps on the Google play store. For carrying out this analysis, we will be assessing factors such as age, type, category, price. Google, has often strategically used its pricing and rating analysis to select the Apps that it needs to keep on its play store. We are using ratings as one of the attributes to assess the success rate of apps on the Google Play store, which is used by most of the Android electronics and is a market leader in this segment

This query analyzes the top 10 installations per genre to determine the most popular genre of apps on google app store. We found that apps that fit the tools genre, Example: Hotspot and free, are the most popular. Entertainment came across as the second most popular.

In [69]:
%%bq query -n Number_of_Installs_Top10

SELECT sum(Installs) AS Number_of_Installs, Genres,
CASE WHEN sum(Installs) > 10000000000 THEN 'Popular'
WHEN sum (Installs)> 5000000000 AND sum (Installs) <  10000000000 THEN 'Moderate'
WHEN sum (Installs) > 1000000000 AND sum (Installs) < 5000000000  THEN 'Fair'
ELSE 'Not Popular'
END AS Popularity_Levels 
FROM `ba770team1.googleplaystore.newdata`
GROUP BY Genres
ORDER BY Number_of_Installs DESC
limit 10

%%bq query 
select type, Sum(Installs) as Sum_installs, AVG(Installs) as AVG_instlls, Avg(Reviews) as Avg_review, Avg(Rating) as Avg_Rating
FROM `ba770team1.googleplaystore.newdata`
where Type = 'Free' and Rating <> 0
group by Type
Union all

where Type = 'Paid' and Rating <> 0
group by type

In this part, we try to check whether the app for children or app for adults are more popular. In order to know that, we divide all the observation according to their users’ age, which is ContentRating in the table, and calculate the average installs number of these several age.

We can grab the information from the columns that the app for everyone, everyone 10+, mature 17+, adults only 18+, respectively has the average installs volume of a little bit more than 10,000,000, more than 30,000,000, about 10,000,000 and 600,000. Based on this result, we can include that from everyone 10+ to adults only, as we cut down the younger population, the average installs will decreases obviously, which means apps will be more popular in younger people.

In [4]:
%%bq query
with sub_critical as 
(select App, ContentRating, Rating, Installs,Price 
from `ba770team1.googleplaystore.newdata` )

select ContentRating, avg(Rating) as avg_rating,
case  when avg(Rating)>4.2 then 'Very Good'
      when avg(Rating)>4 and avg(Rating)<=4.2 then 'Good'
      when avg(Rating)>3.8 and avg(Rating) <=4 then 'Fair'
      when avg(Rating)>3.6 and avg(Rating) <=3.8 then 'Not Good'
      else 'Poor' 
      end as Level
from sub_critical
group by ContentRating
order by avg_rating desc

%%bq query
SELECT   
    AndroidVersion,

    AVG(Rating) AS avg_rating,
   CASE WHEN AVG(Rating) > 4.0 THEN 'Very Good'
      WHEN  AVG(Rating) > 3.5 and AVG(Rating) <= 4.0 THEN 'Good'
      WHEN AVG(Rating) > 3.0 and AVG(Rating) <= 3.5 THEN 'Fair'
      WHEN AVG(Rating) > 2.5 and AVG(Rating) <= 3.0 THEN 'Not Good'
      ELSE 'Poor' 
      END AS Rating
FROM `ba770team1.googleplaystore.newdata`
Group by AndroidVersion

In [47]:
%%bq query

with Rating as 
(select
  Category,
    case when rating= 5 then 'rating is 5'
       when rating>=4 then 'rating around 4'
       when Rating >= 3 and Rating<4 then "rating around 3"
       when Rating >= 2 and Rating<3 then "rating around 2"
       when Rating >= 1 and Rating<2 then "rating around 1"
       when Rating >0 and Rating<1 then 'rating less than 1 or equal to 0'
       when Rating =0 then 'no rating'
       end as Rating_Range
from `googleplaystore.newdata` )
select Rating_Range, count(Category) as amount_of_category,
STRING_AGG(Distinct Category, "-" limit 5) as top_category
from Rating
group by Rating_Range
order by amount_of_category Desc

%%bq query -n raing_and_category

select 
  case when rating= 5 then 'rating is 5'
       when rating >=4 then 'rating around 4'
       when Rating >= 3 and Rating<4 then "rating around 3"
       when Rating >= 2 and Rating<3 then "rating around 2"
       when Rating >= 1 and Rating<2 then "rating around 1"
       when Rating >0 and Rating<1 then 'rating less than 1 or equal to 0'
       when Rating =0 then 'no rating'
       end as Rating_Range,
 count(Category) as amount_of_category
FROM `ba770team1.googleplaystore.newdata` 
group by Rating_Range
order by amount_of_category desc
